title: Respect SET/RESET SESSION queries
body:
According #32, parameters can already be set via `dbConnect(..., parameters = list(...)`.

The Python implementation of Presto API appears to respect [`SET/RESET SESSION ...`](https://prestodb.io/docs/current/sql/set-session.html) query commands directly. This PR does the same for RPResto according to [HTTP Protocol](https://github.com/prestodb/presto/wiki/HTTP-Protocol) specification.

One caveat is this is only possible via `dbGetQuery` due to the API behavior, where parameters are managed by the client instead of the server.

I had to add a new RCpp function to ensure parameters are updated in-place instead of being copied upon modification inside the function.
Furthermore, `PrestoResult` doesn't have access to the connection object and therefore gains a new function slot to do the update.

Test cases are added and tested with a local cluster.

Updated to Roxygen 6.0.1

title: Wrap the `sql` argument to `db_query_fields` with a `sql_subquery`
body:
There is some behavioral change between dplyr 0.4.3 and 0.5.0
in the `sql` argument to `db_query_fields`. If it is a subquery (as
opposed to a table name), it is no longer wrapped in parentheses. We
then end up with an invalid SQL string that looks like:

    SELECT * FROM SELECT ...

Wrapping it with `sql_subquery` fixes the issue for 0.5.0. It still
works for 0.4.3, since it just adds another pair of parentheses.

Now that `httr` dropped `RCurl` dependency, `RPresto` can drop one more dependency by using `base64decode` from `openssl` instead of `RCurl`.

This is PR is motivated by repeated issues my colleagues and I faced when installing `RCurl`. We often get 404 error like this one: https://github.com/swirldev/swirl/issues/291 
I know this is likely a CRAN mirror issue instead but one less dependency one less thing to worry about 😆 

Also one of the tests failed on me and it looks like due to some `dplyr` changes:

title: Handle Decimal type as character
body:
Storing the decimal type as a number doesn't actually make sense since that type
more closely matches a double. Furthermore Presto encodes the decimal type in
the JSON response as a string so in order to keep the arbitrary precision of the
type we need to store is a character. Users can then use their favorite
arbitrary precision library to convert the string into that class.

Fixes #60

title: Use Rcpp for 10x faster data.frame conversion
body:
Move row iterations from R to Rcpp for 10x speedup. `check_names` verify column names are consistent and each row contains exactly required columns. `transpose` convert a row major list of list to a column major list of list. It also handles null to NA conversion for inner lists and special numerical values. Because assignment is made in-place whenever possible, this is much faster than the replaced R implementation.

Fix #33 hopefully. I not well-versed in Rcpp so feedbacks and suggestions are really appreciated. Initial profiling result seems promising, for exact same query in #57:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4317392/16144540/81d20fbc-3428-11e6-9808-e85e71bb0e1b.png)

`.extract.data` nows takes about the same time as raw JSON parsing and is 10x faster compared to original runtime and profiler credits `.tranpose` 20ms out of 110ms (note 10ms is minimal resolution). 
I still need to take a look at bigint and add some test cases for named/unnamed list but feel free to try this out and let me know if this fixes the performance issue or if it outputs garbage.

title: use native class check for .null.to.na
body:
`.null.to.na` takes majority of the time spent in `.extract.data` in a presto query. By using native `is.null` and `is.list` checks can speed up the function up to 2x. Raw typed column checking was the next hotspot in the function. By moving it outside, we gain additional non-negligible speed up.

This partially addresses #33. Here is profiling of a Presto query that returns relative large result set (~100k) before and after.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4317392/16136185/6401ddb4-33dd-11e6-96dc-54ff8edaabfd.png)

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4317392/16136188/6a82d80a-33dd-11e6-8225-ab0ec5d88f14.png)

As we can see, `.extract.data` takes significant amount of time of the function even after the optimization. After this change, most time is spent in copying data row by row `rv[[j]][[i]] <- .null.to.na(row[[j]])`. I wonder if we can do something with Rcpp to make this even better.

title: Add warning for integer columns being corrupted by lacking 64-bit integer support
body:
Presto BIGINT columns support 64-bit integers, whereas R is still
lacking full support for them. R silently casts any such value to a
double, which leads to loss of precision and is impossible to recover
afterwards.

jsonlite solves this by utilizing the bit64 package. That approach has
lots of caveats though, so we need to investigate more to see if we can
do the same.

As #25 identified, some tests were failing when locale was not en_US.utf-8.

The issues were mostly around encodings of strings in the test cases.

```
library('dplyr'); library('DBI'); devtools::load_all('~/local/repositories/RPresto'); devtools::test('~/local/repositories/RPresto')

```

title: Support for proper session time zone handling
body:
Presto allows the setting of the timezone through the X-Presto-Time-Zone
header, we add proper support for that.

The session timezone is mainly used when:
- parsing strings as timestamps
- Timestamp representations of hive 'TIMESTAMP' columns (which are
  internally stored as unix times)
- Interval calculations on timestamp fields

See the discussion in #25.

My current approach is to automatically infer the time zone from the R session when available.
If that's not available through Sys.timezone() (which will unfortunately be the case most of the time), we give a warning and let presto assign its default.

I'm not sure about this behavior, since I imagine the warnings could be rather annoying.
Another alternative is to make the default 'UTC', clearly document this, and only change it if explicitly specified during dbConnect().
@cosinequanon, any thoughts?

@dain, could you check tests/testthat/test-session.timezone.R and
verify that my 'expected values' for the test cases are correct?

title: dbDataType's first argument should be DBIDriver
body:
With this I also switched to calling dbDataType directly instead of using db_data_type. Using real objects is rather tricky with the 'fields' argument for that function.
It's actually quite easy to misuse since list() is a valid argument to dbDataType for the PrestoDriver.
So we might want to disable/remove db_data_type until there is a more significant need.

Note that this PR stacks on top of #26.
